WEBVTT

00:00:00.260 --> 00:00:00.590
...

00:00:00.590 --> 00:00:05.360
trying to migrate a community to Blue Sky, and we

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:08.080
wanted to hear from other people that are also working with their

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:10.910
communities and trying to build community on Blue Sky, and we

00:00:10.910 --> 00:00:14.350
're on Twitter, or other social networks, and hear from

00:00:14.350 --> 00:00:17.740
you also, what works, what insights do you have from

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:19.280
your experience?

00:00:19.860 --> 00:00:22.620
So, I'll start, and I'll kind of continue

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:26.190
that question about Sky Follower Bridge, so I think

00:00:26.210 --> 00:00:29.100
that's a really cool tool, but I think one of

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:33.280
the challenges with it is if people are joining after you've

00:00:33.280 --> 00:00:36.150
searched, then they don't appear.

00:00:36.390 --> 00:00:38.990
You have to go research, so I'm a PhD student

00:00:38.990 --> 00:00:41.990
, but I've, on the side, been slowly working

00:00:41.990 --> 00:00:45.220
towards a tool that is, it has to work similarly in

00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:47.840
the case of X, because X, you can't export

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.190
your followers and get username handles.

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:53.920
It gives you gibberish numbers.

00:00:54.180 --> 00:00:59.330
Other platforms, they do actually export user handles, so there

00:00:59.330 --> 00:01:04.330
's a little bit of complexity there in terms of data management

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:06.140
from EU programs.

00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:09.810
And so, I've been thinking through a little bit of

00:01:09.850 --> 00:01:12.800
this, I kind of did a vibe-coded version

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:16.200
, and now I'm slowly thinking through building this up as

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:20.160
an actual system, where Blue Sky, and Skylight,

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:24.490
and all these different AT protocol apps can actually implement this as

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:27.090
a notification that you can get, "Oh, someone just

00:01:27.090 --> 00:01:30.970
joined." Now you can follow them, or automatically follow them

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:32.120
, or whatever.

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:35.960
So, there's a lot of really cool implementations,

00:01:35.960 --> 00:01:38.640
too, of like, verifying that you are who,

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:42.290
you as your Blue Sky handle and your DID, you're

00:01:42.310 --> 00:01:46.210
associated with this LinkedIn account, and if we can get that

00:01:46.210 --> 00:01:51.730
as like, a verified, authenticated match, that makes

00:01:51.730 --> 00:01:54.590
it a lot easier to find those matches, because sometimes the

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:57.280
handles are a little bit different, especially since we can have

00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:01.600
domain handles on Blue Sky, that changes the equation a little

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:01.880
bit.

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:04.860
So, that is something I've been thinking about personally,

00:02:04.860 --> 00:02:07.450
and trying to like, move people over, is like,

00:02:07.450 --> 00:02:10.670
I want to be notified when someone is coming to Blue Sky

00:02:10.670 --> 00:02:13.280
, and not only that, I want them sorted in order

00:02:13.330 --> 00:02:16.880
of who's actually posting, not just who's here.

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:19.010
I think that would also help with what you said, Scott

00:02:19.010 --> 00:02:20.890
, like, if someone moves over to Blue Sky, and

00:02:20.890 --> 00:02:23.320
people get notified, they would get followed, and then you

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:25.790
get that dopamine hit of like, "Oh, people are

00:02:25.790 --> 00:02:28.250
engaging with me, and they like to see me here."

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:29.880
So, yeah, there's something there, maybe.

00:02:30.140 --> 00:02:32.990
Yeah, and I think I want to pick up on one

00:02:32.990 --> 00:02:37.350
thing that we'll probably need to engage with, like,

00:02:37.430 --> 00:02:41.290
almost kind of a hosting, like, the welcoming committee,

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:44.880
if you will, you know, kind of that piece.

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:47.490
Because that was a common refrain I heard, like, "

00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:49.880
Oh, it's just that I don't get engagement.

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:52.100
Nobody, you know, like, nothing happens." And it

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:53.610
's like, "Well, yeah, you're new."

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:55.860
And, you know, like, you might have had,

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:59.450
you know, other platforms, and they engaged in a certain

00:02:59.450 --> 00:02:59.880
way.

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:02.460
Or that kind of fertile ground to have people that kind of

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:04.370
are engaging, like, "Oh, yeah, let's

00:03:04.370 --> 00:03:07.240
jump in, like, welcome." I remember, like,

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:11.220
during the entire phase of when we were trying, when we

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:14.880
, you know, in beta, when we still had the

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:16.710
invites, and we're bringing people over for Science Twitter and

00:03:16.710 --> 00:03:19.250
that, you know, people actually set up, like,

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:21.730
you know, Hi SciSky, where it's like

00:03:21.730 --> 00:03:22.880
, "You're new here.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:25.860
Tell us what you do." And that, I think,

00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:27.880
was one of the ways that kind of set the ground a

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:27.880
little bit.

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:29.430
It was like, "Yeah, this is what I do

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:31.430
." And you just, you kind of follow that, and

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:32.880
enough people were doing it.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:35.480
You didn't necessarily have to have the entire community do it

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:38.320
, but the bigger ecosystem was kind of popping in, and

00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:43.180
saying, "We're glad you're here." So,

00:03:43.180 --> 00:03:45.860
I guess, how am I supposed to hold this?

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:48.860
