00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:28.880
benefit.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:30.530
And I ran into that several times when I'm trying to

00:12:30.570 --> 00:12:33.280
explain to people, it's like finding that balance of like

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:34.860
, you want to try it.

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:37.910
And like, you know, people might, you know,

00:12:37.910 --> 00:12:41.050
for example, a kind of ventilated seat in your car

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:42.880
, like, why would I ever need that?

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:43.880
You take a three hour drive.

00:12:44.140 --> 00:12:47.820
You're like, oh, yeah, yeah, now I

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:48.880
get it.

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:52.220
But you got to be there to try it out because otherwise

00:12:52.220 --> 00:12:53.880
it just doesn't click.

00:12:54.100 --> 00:12:59.880
So yeah, thinking about like junior researchers, younger people,

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:02.040
again, there's this, there's kind of the marketing

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:04.930
problem of like blue skies scene, I guess, is like

00:13:04.930 --> 00:13:05.880
millennial.

00:13:06.100 --> 00:13:08.590
And I don't know, I can't solve that problem

00:13:08.590 --> 00:13:08.860
.

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:10.880
I don't know what to do about that.

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:13.860
But then we've tried to get feedback.

00:13:13.950 --> 00:13:17.720
I try to talk to more junior students, younger people about

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:21.450
like, how they feel about social media, and blue sky

00:13:21.450 --> 00:13:22.860
in particular.

00:13:23.110 --> 00:13:25.860
And I wouldn't say I have like a full picture.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:28.140
But part of what I hear, well, part of it

00:13:28.140 --> 00:13:30.880
, I think is just, in general, the community is

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:31.880
fractured.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:34.770
And there are other things going on, especially in the US

00:13:34.770 --> 00:13:38.360
, where like anyone on a visa posting on social media at

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:43.880
all is a very scary, potentially very high consequence act right

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:44.880
now.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:46.880
So there's that whole background.

00:13:47.090 --> 00:13:49.540
But usually what I hear is like, oh, it feels

00:13:49.540 --> 00:13:52.880
scary or feels like you're up on a stage or,

00:13:53.070 --> 00:13:55.230
and to some extent, I do think we have some new

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:57.880
challenges like what I was just mentioning.

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:01.930
But also some of these are just, they actually may not

00:14:01.930 --> 00:14:03.880
be unique to right now.

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:06.060
And I can remember when I was a junior student, I

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:06.860
just lurked.

00:14:06.990 --> 00:14:08.880
Of course, yeah, I also felt nervous.

00:14:09.010 --> 00:14:10.660
And I wasn't going to just like chime in to random

00:14:10.830 --> 00:14:12.880
conversations between senior researchers.

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:13.880
I lurked.

00:14:14.050 --> 00:14:14.880
And that was fine.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:15.880
And I gained a lot from that.

00:14:15.990 --> 00:14:17.890
So there needs to be, so maybe on one hand,

00:14:17.890 --> 00:14:20.880
like, it's okay, that's not a new thing

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:24.920
for people newer to a community to be more nervous about posting

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:26.880
or joining, interacting in the community.

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:31.010
But then what we can do as more senior people or people

00:14:31.100 --> 00:14:33.860
who are more comfortable posting and being active is to, you

00:14:33.860 --> 00:14:37.880
know, give them something to gain from being there.

00:14:37.990 --> 00:14:41.710
So interacting with each other, having conversations, posting about papers

00:14:41.770 --> 00:14:45.510
, posting papers of junior researchers, and trying to also build

00:14:45.920 --> 00:14:50.880
infrastructure to support that kind of sharing or encourage that kind of

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:50.880
sharing.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:54.010
I think that's one of the reasons that Paper Sky Jest

00:14:54.010 --> 00:14:54.880
is so great, right?

00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:56.880
Like highlighting papers.

00:14:57.140 --> 00:14:59.860
And that gives a clear gain to people.

00:15:00.120 --> 00:15:05.120
So I'm actually not that much younger, really, but

00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:06.880
I am a current PhD student.

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:10.490
And since I was, like, applying, you know,

00:15:10.530 --> 00:15:12.880
a few years ago, or I don't know what time

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:12.880
is.

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:13.880
Four years ago?

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:14.880
Oh, God.

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:15.880
Yeah.

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:17.880
So I was applying, like, five years ago.

00:15:18.060 --> 00:15:20.050
And what I can say is that I was pretty much on

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:20.860
Instagram.

00:15:21.050 --> 00:15:23.860
So it's a very visual-based community.

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:31.540
But there is a very large, wonderful ecosystem of women scientists

00:15:31.540 --> 00:15:36.250
, scientists, communicators, who were posting things to just

00:15:36.250 --> 00:15:40.880
help other -- these were PhD students who had just started posting

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:45.010
to help other people who were interested in PhDs to get

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:48.120
into their PhD programs, just talking about their experiences, talking

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:51.870
about the different types of programs, different situations that occur with

00:15:51.870 --> 00:15:54.720
all the different programs that exist, and that kind of thing

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:54.880
.

00:15:55.140 --> 00:16:00.440
And what I found is most of them are still on Instagram

00:16:00.440 --> 00:16:00.880
.

00:16:00.980 --> 00:16:04.430
I've seen a few try to come over, and they

00:16:04.570 --> 00:16:06.880
don't get engagement.

00:16:07.020 --> 00:16:08.880
So they're like, why be here?

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:12.030
Because there's also a fair amount of overlap with, okay

00:16:12.030 --> 00:16:13.880
, like, how can I use this to monetize?

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:16.860
Like, how can I use this for extra income?

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:17.880
I'm a PhD student.

00:16:17.950 --> 00:16:19.880
I don't have a lot of free time.

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:22.150
So if I'm going to be making this content, that

00:16:22.150 --> 00:16:23.880
content takes a lot of time.

00:16:23.950 --> 00:16:24.880
I've done it.

00:16:25.030 --> 00:16:28.140
It takes a lot of time to make the quality content that

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:29.880
these students were making.

00:16:30.140 --> 00:16:34.150
And so being able to kind of get some incentive to do

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:36.880
that is pretty beneficial.

00:16:37.030 --> 00:16:39.980
So if you come over from Instagram to Blue Sky, and

00:16:39.980 --> 00:16:42.270
then no one's liking anything, it's just kind of

00:16:42.270 --> 00:16:44.530
like, I'm not making money and no one's seeing

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:44.880
it.

00:16:45.110 --> 00:16:45.880
What's the point?

00:16:46.030 --> 00:16:48.780
So one of the things I've been trying to work on

00:16:48.780 --> 00:16:51.880
is a custom feed that's PhD chatter.

00:16:52.030 --> 00:16:53.950
And I know on Twitter, like, people just, like

00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:54.860
, used a hashtag.

00:16:55.060 --> 00:16:57.860
And then over time, it became, like, algorithmic

00:16:57.890 --> 00:17:00.880
where you didn't necessarily need to do that.

00:17:01.120 --> 00:17:04.230
And so kind of what people did when they came over to

00:17:04.240 --> 00:17:07.880
Blue Sky was just try to do hashtag-based feeds.

00:17:08.030 --> 00:17:10.570
But what ends up happening is those end up being chronological

00:17:10.570 --> 00:17:13.880
feeds where people aren't getting the content that they want.

00:17:14.140 --> 00:17:17.310
Like, it kind of sometimes feels like you're getting ad

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:18.880
blasted a little bit.

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:23.430
And so what I've been working on is more of a

00:17:23.630 --> 00:17:28.670
regex, like, semantic style matching of, like

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:30.730
, language, like, common language that you might use when

00:17:30.830 --> 00:17:34.680
talking about research, when talking about your dissertation, your PhD

00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:39.880
paper, what you're doing in your academic career.

00:17:40.120 --> 00:17:43.690
And then filtering that from people's bios to just pull in

00:17:43.720 --> 00:17:44.880
, okay, this is a PhD student.

00:17:45.140 --> 00:17:47.860
Let's filter out the professors.

00:17:48.060 --> 00:17:50.860
But I think even if you're filtering out the professors,

00:17:50.890 --> 00:17:54.350
sometimes knowing that they can see it is a little bit of

00:17:54.350 --> 00:17:54.880
a deterrent.

00:17:55.140 --> 00:17:59.190
Because, especially as an undergrad, I know, I was

00:17:59.220 --> 00:18:03.990
, like, the brief moments I spent on Twitter actually was

00:18:03.990 --> 00:18:04.860
probably pre-undergrad.

00:18:05.100 --> 00:18:08.140
And, like, I wouldn't want any professor or teacher

00:18:08.140 --> 00:18:09.880
seeing what I was saying.

00:18:09.980 --> 00:18:13.880
I was just whining because I needed to whine.

00:18:14.070 --> 00:18:16.380
And so I think we also need those, like, closed

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:22.020
permission spaces really to attract different groups, to give them that

00:18:22.030 --> 00:18:24.880
space to be free and feel comfortable.

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:28.480
But we also need to kind of, like, grow how

00:18:28.570 --> 00:18:31.880
do we get people to find these feeds?

00:18:32.120 --> 00:18:33.880
The search is not very good.

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:38.880
And so how do we get people even exposed to these things

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:38.880
?

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:43.350
And finding the people that they can connect with that aren't

00:18:43.660 --> 00:18:46.880
necessarily people they're already connected with.

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:51.530
And I think that was a thing people found Twitter very useful

00:18:51.660 --> 00:18:58.860
for that hasn't necessarily existed as much yet on Blue Sky

00:18:58.940 --> 00:19:00.880
, at least in the academic sense.

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:06.440
I think that's very much been building up from existing networks

00:19:06.440 --> 00:19:10.870
rather than trying to expand and grow networks.

00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:13.190
I know Eugene has a practice of, like, trying to

00:19:13.190 --> 00:19:15.880
find junior researchers' papers and posting about them.

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:19.410
And maybe we could do more of that somehow and make it

00:19:19.430 --> 00:19:21.880
more, like, I don't know, feeds that promote

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:25.870
young researchers or give them more engagement somehow.

00:19:26.140 --> 00:19:28.950
Yeah, I think, again, gain or showing, like

00:19:28.950 --> 00:19:32.150
, I've, through Blue Sky, got to know some

00:19:32.250 --> 00:19:33.880
junior PhD students.

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:36.120
And we're now collaborating through, like, you know,

00:19:36.120 --> 00:19:37.880
nice little social media interactions.

00:19:38.070 --> 00:19:41.430
So, I don't know, somehow, like, showing

00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:44.880
the rest of them that this is possible.

00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:47.860
It's to your benefit to be posting about stuff.

00:19:48.140 --> 00:19:50.860
You want people to see your papers.

00:19:51.140 --> 00:19:52.980
There's a lot to gain by being on there, even

00:19:52.980 --> 00:19:54.880
if you aren't posting all the time.

00:19:55.610 --> 00:20:01.880
There's a nice hack.

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:05.830
Barely a hack, but replying to people on the

00:20:05.830 --> 00:20:09.570
topic of, oh, you know, making content is expensive

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:09.880
.

00:20:10.140 --> 00:20:11.880
Nobody sees my posts.

00:20:12.090 --> 00:20:14.050
When you're a small account, you want to reply to

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:14.880
bigger accounts.

00:20:15.090 --> 00:20:17.810
And that's kind of how you give yourself to know for

00:20:17.850 --> 00:20:18.880
other people.

00:20:19.140 --> 00:20:23.960
And, you know, this, you can have good reply

00:20:23.960 --> 00:20:25.880
game, right?

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:28.630
Like, you've got to, you've got to reply

00:20:28.630 --> 00:20:30.880
properly, like, like, it's improv or something.

00:20:31.030 --> 00:20:32.520
You know, like, in a yes and kind of way

00:20:32.530 --> 00:20:34.880
, you want to be supporting the person you're replying

00:20:34.880 --> 00:20:35.880
to.

00:20:36.070 --> 00:20:38.860
You want to be adding something to the conversation.

00:20:39.140 --> 00:20:43.270
And this is one of, you know, a basket of

00:20:43.660 --> 00:20:49.060
norms that kind of support a generative, like, intellectual

00:20:49.060 --> 00:20:50.860
environment online, right?

00:20:51.130 --> 00:20:54.710
And the norms aren't necessarily the same as they are in

00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:58.890
real life because you have a different set of affordances,

00:20:58.890 --> 00:20:59.880
you know.

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:02.810
I almost wonder if that's a way that you can kind

00:21:02.850 --> 00:21:05.710
of build this up is, you know, we have these

00:21:05.710 --> 00:21:12.600
, you know, kind of pitches and sessions usually at conferences

00:21:12.600 --> 00:21:15.460
where it's like kind of the junior members and students,

00:21:15.460 --> 00:21:16.880
you know, how do you kickstart your career?

00:21:17.140 --> 00:21:19.860
This would be valuable content.

00:21:20.140 --> 00:21:22.500
Like, I mean, it, I think that's one

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:26.720
of the age pieces is like Twitter started off like nobody knew

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:27.880
what it was.

00:21:28.080 --> 00:21:30.430
And it kind of evolved into like, oh, this can

00:21:30.430 --> 00:21:31.880
actually be powerful.

00:21:32.140 --> 00:21:34.960
And so I think you're, if we'd all rolled

00:21:34.960 --> 00:21:38.880
the clock back, you know, five or 10 years,

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:40.580
and we're like, we were coming in from this,

00:21:40.580 --> 00:21:42.080
like, okay, I need to do this, but I

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:42.860
don't know how.

00:21:43.140 --> 00:21:46.880
And, like, I don't want to mess up.

00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:50.230
And I think, and, like, particularly in, you

00:21:50.240 --> 00:21:54.880
know, Twitter, the actual incentive structure is conflict.

00:21:55.030 --> 00:21:57.420
So it is about, like, even if you were,

00:21:57.420 --> 00:22:00.710
like, an undergrad, you might have somebody jump on you

00:22:00.710 --> 00:22:03.420
out of the blue with this huge account, and you're

00:22:03.420 --> 00:22:04.870
just like, what did I do?

00:22:05.080 --> 00:22:07.200
And that's why I think, like, you know,

00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:10.700
the Leah features are phenomenal in that way, because it is

00:22:10.700 --> 00:22:13.530
in that sense, like, let's give you a little

00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:14.860
bit more control.

00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:16.880
Like, like, do you want to stand up?

00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:17.880
Like, no, that's wrong.

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:18.880
And here's why.

00:22:18.970 --> 00:22:19.880
And, like, I'm going to get in this.

00:22:20.020 --> 00:22:21.980
Or, like, I'm not up for this, and

00:22:21.980 --> 00:22:24.880
I just need you to go away before this goes on.

00:22:25.110 --> 00:22:28.050
And so you have that lever, which I think could be

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:31.880
a piece that does help cultivate the next generation.

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:34.810
I'm just having one more thought about this right now,

00:22:34.850 --> 00:22:36.880
which is, like, maybe it's just all wrong,

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:40.170
especially for, like, if we're not the junior people

00:22:40.170 --> 00:22:41.860
, to be worrying about why aren't junior people?

00:22:42.140 --> 00:22:43.880
How do we make it cool?

00:22:44.020 --> 00:22:45.730
And instead, like, I could think, you know,

00:22:45.790 --> 00:22:47.810
any academic in the room, if you've organized a talk

00:22:47.810 --> 00:22:49.360
series or a cloakroom, you're like, why is

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:49.880
no one coming?

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:50.880
How do I get this?

00:22:51.090 --> 00:22:52.880
Like, you need to get the faculty to come.

00:22:53.020 --> 00:22:55.860
If their advisors are on blue sky, they're going to

00:22:55.890 --> 00:22:56.880
be on blue sky.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:58.880
So maybe we should just focus on that.

00:22:59.060 --> 00:23:02.270
How do we get the senior researchers who are comfortable posting,

00:23:02.270 --> 00:23:05.340
clearly, because they're posting on X or LinkedIn, how

00:23:05.340 --> 00:23:08.870
do we get them on blue sky?

00:23:09.120 --> 00:23:12.990
We can open it up to the crowd, if you want

00:23:12.990 --> 00:23:15.880
to talk, ask questions.

00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:18.690
And I think there's a really good point about that it

00:23:18.690 --> 00:23:21.880
's hard as a senior academic to know what's necessary.

00:23:21.970 --> 00:23:26.010
I was thinking about how we can also avoid turning up like

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:28.880
a square peg into a round hole with content.

00:23:29.070 --> 00:23:33.350
So maybe the solution for people of early career, frankly,

00:23:33.350 --> 00:23:35.880
to see there are a lot of different trends here.

00:23:35.880 --> 00:23:38.710
I think there are a lot of different things that we can

00:23:38.710 --> 00:23:41.710
do, and I don't remember what we can do these

00:23:41.710 --> 00:23:42.880
days.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:45.200
I think I see things like the group chats that are far

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:47.960
more popular, and people generally don't have more contacts,

00:23:47.960 --> 00:23:48.880
and you can post your faces.

00:23:49.140 --> 00:23:51.860
What is it that you can say for a national value?

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:55.680
I think it makes me wonder if things like really could somehow

00:23:55.680 --> 00:23:58.180
be adapted to work to the kind of landscape space, and

00:23:58.190 --> 00:24:02.270
having to describe a chat spaces for the person, but also

00:24:02.270 --> 00:24:05.350
make things like having to be pressuring on these things about

00:24:05.430 --> 00:24:05.880
bias.

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:08.210
I think we're really missing out in this country that there

00:24:08.210 --> 00:24:08.880
's a group here.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:12.270
We're looking out on these kind of abilities to have these

00:24:12.300 --> 00:24:13.880
more close, safe spaces.

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:17.340
Because I agree with Ireland that I think a lot of how

00:24:17.340 --> 00:24:20.880
unsafe I thought you wanted to spend the rest of it online

00:24:20.880 --> 00:24:20.880
.

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:23.520
It's safe to pass it from so you can see it

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:25.880
, and you're really great by it.

00:24:26.610 --> 00:24:29.880
Hi.

00:24:30.140 --> 00:24:30.880
Hi.

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:34.880
What is that?

00:24:35.620 --> 00:24:37.870
Sorry?

00:24:38.020 --> 00:24:41.670
So to summarize kind of the comment and question for the stream

00:24:41.670 --> 00:24:47.060
, Emily was just kind of reiterating the point of,

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:50.880
okay, yeah, as an undergrad, it was so overwhelming

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:53.980
to be able to post, and then know some big professor

00:24:53.980 --> 00:24:56.880
could see this and do something about it.

00:24:57.140 --> 00:25:01.770
Maybe we can use Rumi as a potential avenue for providing

00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:06.870
group chats, which seem maybe more popular with the younger generations

00:25:06.880 --> 00:25:10.050
, and provide a more private space for them to interact while

00:25:10.050 --> 00:25:15.880
still being on the same platform where their professors are.

00:25:16.050 --> 00:25:18.860
So I don't actually know what Rumi does.

00:25:18.880 --> 00:25:21.490
I'm assuming it's like-- It's like Discord on

00:25:21.490 --> 00:25:21.880
APRA.

00:25:21.990 --> 00:25:22.880
It's like Discord.

00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:23.880
Cool.

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:24.880
Yeah.

00:25:25.120 --> 00:25:27.470
Well, I think a lot about the dark forest problem,

00:25:27.470 --> 00:25:31.690
which is basically this, that the open internet, you know

00:25:31.690 --> 00:25:33.880
, opens you up to surveillance and wanted attention.

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:38.190
And, you know, there's the dark forest collective who

00:25:38.240 --> 00:25:40.880
kind of write about this a bit.

00:25:41.140 --> 00:25:44.430
And then the usual answer they give is, oh, people

00:25:44.570 --> 00:25:46.880
retreat to the cozy web, which is group chats.

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:47.880
Right?

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:51.530
One thing that bothers me about that solution is that you don

00:25:51.560 --> 00:25:52.880
't get discovery.

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:56.600
And, you know, the contributions you make in the safety

00:25:56.600 --> 00:26:00.880
of your group chat don't necessarily percolate to,

00:26:00.880 --> 00:26:01.880
you know, the knowledge comments.

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:02.880
Right?

00:26:03.140 --> 00:26:06.870
Unless someone takes the link you just posted or takes a screenshot

00:26:06.870 --> 00:26:08.880
and repost it to some other group chat.

00:26:09.100 --> 00:26:13.670
So I think, I think it's really important to figure

00:26:13.670 --> 00:26:18.540
out if there's something in between, you know, the

00:26:18.630 --> 00:26:21.880
open internet and group chats.

00:26:22.140 --> 00:26:25.530
And I think we have someone from Rumi in the room

00:26:25.570 --> 00:26:25.880
.

